Problem: Duplicate Telegram transaction entries

What happened:
When a user sent a Telegram command like "expense coffee 6.50 food", the bot created a new MongoDB transaction every time it processed that message. If Telegram delivered the same update twice, Render restarted during processing, or two bot instances briefly ran with the same BOT_TOKEN, the same command could create duplicate entries.

Root cause:
The Transaction document did not store the Telegram message identity. The bot had no way to know whether a specific Telegram chat/message pair had already been processed.

Solution:
Each Telegram-created transaction now stores:
- source: "telegram"
- telegramChatId
- telegramUserId
- telegramMessageId

Before creating a transaction, the bot checks for an existing Transaction with the same telegramChatId and telegramMessageId. If one exists, the bot skips creation and replies that the message was already saved.

Extra database protection:
The Transaction schema now has a unique partial index on:
- telegramChatId
- telegramMessageId

That prevents duplicate Telegram messages from creating duplicate records even if two bot processes try to save the same update at nearly the same time.

Operational note:
Only one polling bot instance should run with a BOT_TOKEN. In production, keep the Render bot running and stop any local server using the same token.

Problem: Old Telegram update created an unexpected transaction

What happened:
After the bot started or reconnected, Telegram could deliver an older pending update that was sent before the current bot process started. If that old update was an expense or income command, the bot could save it even though the user was expecting only their new query to run.

Root cause:
Telegram polling works like a mailbox. Messages that were not consumed while the bot was offline or restarting can still be waiting. The bot did not check whether a message was older than the current process startup time.

Solution:
The bot now records a startup timestamp:
- botStartedAt

Before handling any Telegram message, it checks:
- if msg.date is older than botStartedAt, ignore it

This prevents old queued Telegram commands from creating surprise transactions after a Render restart or local bot restart.

Problem: Telegram recent and summary commands did not work as slash commands

What happened:
Users expected Telegram commands like "/summary" and "/recent" to work from the Telegram command menu, but the bot only recognized plain text messages like "summary" and "recent".

Root cause:
The bot command matching only accepted the exact words:
- summary
- recent

Telegram slash commands include a leading slash, and in some contexts Telegram can include the bot username too, such as:
- /summary
- /summary@TrackerBot
- /recent
- /recent@TrackerBot

Solution:
The bot now accepts both plain text and Telegram slash command versions:
- summary
- /summary
- /summary@BotName
- recent
- /recent
- /recent@BotName

The help text now also shows "/summary" and "/recent" so users know these are real Telegram commands.

Problem: Telegram users had to type the transaction type manually

What happened:
To add a transaction from Telegram, users had to remember the full text format:
- expense coffee 6.50 food
- income paycheck 1200 work

That works, but it is easy to mistype and does not feel like a Telegram-native flow.

Root cause:
The bot only handled text commands. It did not offer a button-based choice for the first decision: whether the transaction is income or expense.

Solution:
The bot now supports an "/add" command that sends two Telegram inline buttons:
- Income
- Expense

When a user taps one of those buttons, the bot stores the selected transaction type for that chat. The next plain message from that chat is treated as the transaction details.

Example:
1. User sends "/add"
2. User taps "Expense"
3. Bot asks for details
4. User sends "coffee 6.50 food"
5. Bot saves it as "expense coffee 6.50 food"

The bot also supports "/cancel" to clear the current button entry if the user changes their mind.

Problem: Telegram transaction chats stayed cluttered after commands

What happened:
The Telegram chat kept every command and bot reply, including:
- /add
- the Income and Expense button prompt
- the detail instruction message
- the user's transaction details
- the saved transaction confirmation
- the recent transaction summary

Root cause:
Telegram bots do not have a "clear history" API. They can only delete specific messages by chat id and message id. The bot was sending and receiving messages without scheduling those individual messages for cleanup.

Solution:
The bot now schedules Telegram messages for deletion after 5 minutes.

It does this for:
- incoming user messages after the bot confirms they are current messages
- bot replies sent through the auto-deleting message helper
- button prompt messages
- instruction messages
- confirmation and summary messages
- error/help messages

Important Telegram limitation:
This is not the same as clearing the full chat history. The bot deletes individual messages that it can access. In private chat this should work for both bot replies and incoming user messages. In group chats, Telegram may require the bot to have delete-message permission.

Problem: Telegram Income and Expense button flow crashed after adding auto-delete

What happened:
After the user sent "/add", tapped "Income" or "Expense", and then entered the transaction details, the bot failed instead of saving the transaction.

Root cause:
The auto-delete helper expects this argument order:
- bot
- chatId
- text
- options

Some multi-line calls were accidentally changed to:
- chatId
- text

That meant the helper tried to call sendMessage on the chat id instead of on the Telegram bot instance.

Solution:
Every sendAutoDeletingMessage call now passes the Telegram bot instance first.

Example:
- correct: sendAutoDeletingMessage(bot, chatId, "message")
- wrong: sendAutoDeletingMessage(chatId, "message")

This fixes the button callback flow and the save-confirmation flow after the user enters the amount/details.

Problem: Telegram looked blank after sending /start during deployment

What happened:
The user sent "/start" several times, but no bot message appeared in Telegram.

Root cause:
The bot had a startup guard that ignored every Telegram message older than the current server process. That protected against stale expense/income messages creating surprise transactions, but it also ignored safe commands like:
- /start
- /help
- /add
- /summary
- /recent

If Render was restarting or redeploying, Telegram could queue those safe commands. When the bot came back online, the old-message guard silently dropped them.

Solution:
The bot now still logs old Telegram messages, but it only blocks old messages that could create a transaction:
- expense ...
- income ...
- pending button-entry details

Safe commands like "/start" and "/add" can still reply after a restart.

Extra debugging:
The bot now logs Telegram polling errors. If production has a token conflict, Render logs should show the polling error instead of failing silently.
